comment_data.body: This appends an underscore to all these cnames. We should avoid that in the normal (already unique) case. (Note that we should remove the underscore before testing for uniqueness for the first time.)

```suggestion
                prefix + "large%s_" + value[:18] + "_xxx_" + value[-18:])
```

comment_data.body:
Why not make this a runnable tests? It seems worth testing that the number passes correctly and that we only shorten the cnames (we can probably test that with a tree assertion, looking at the cname attribute of the constant).

It also seems worth testing that the uniqueness algorithm works. This is not currently covered here.

If that test starts failing at some point, we'd better have some diagnostic output.
```suggestion
>>> large_int2 - large_int1 == 10**485  or  large_int2
True
```

Maybe it was lost in the context, but this part is the only thing that was failing, and hopefully it's clear now the point I was making that if this test runs successfully than we can assume that there are no collitions

I think that we can just add a comment to the code to update the test in case the amount of digits left will change
